        "id": "V_36X78P1oNGV3QD",
        "title": "Text 4",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": ["<p>Because the number of gold coins in each pouch is unknown, we can let x represent the number of coins in one pouch. We can let 1 represent the value of one gold coin. Then this situation can be represented with one of the following equivalent equations:</p>"]
        }
      },
      {"id": "IVVQHiRSi06RpaTO", "title": "Text 5", "content": {"type": "Text", "format": "html", "text": ["<p>2x + 4 = 12     or      2(x + 2) = 12      or      x + 2 + x + 2 = 12</p>"]}},
      {"id": "M7L0wV8w29Y5FOfl", "title": "Text 6", "content": {"type": "Text", "format": "html", "text": ["<p>Recall from several of the Grade 6 grade units that we have been solving linear equations of the form y = ax and y = x + b. We used tables, graphs, and numeric reasoning. </p>"]}},
      {
        "id": "R3QKqRg6QFbZXj4S",
        "title": "Text 7",
        "content": {"type": "Text", "format": "html", "text": ["<p>In this Problem, we will revisit problems that involve linear situations with pouches and coins, but we will also use symbolic equations to represent our solution process to equations of the form, </p>"]}
      },
      {"id": "kmyU9ZCHmDI-1Fqi", "title": "Text 8", "content": {"type": "Text", "format": "html", "text": ["<p>y = ax + b     or     ax + b = cx + d.</p>"]}}
